<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="lessons-learned">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>pm</group>
    <domain>project-manager</domain>
    <summary>Continuous knowledge-capture with structured fields (Situation, Impact, Root Cause, Lesson, Recommendation). Lessons stored in versioned repository with application-rate SLO tracking.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>lessons-learned</tag>
      <tag>postmortem</tag>
      <tag>continuous-improvement</tag>
      <tag>knowledge-management</tag>
      <tag>rca</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>knowledge</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Lessons Learned</title>
    <summary>Structured knowledge-capture process that runs continuously throughout a project, not only at close-out. Each lesson requires five fields: Situation (facts), Impact (quantified), Root Cause (5-whys), Lesson (generalizable, two sentences max), Recommendation (action verb + owner role + where applied). Lessons stored in a versioned, searchable repository; application rate tracked as an SLO.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>The canonical failure mode is "captured but never used": lessons sit in a wiki graveyard and the same mistakes recur. Enforcing structured fields with quantified impact prevents vague write-ups ("communication was bad"). Tracking application rate — what percent of last quarter's lessons triggered a process change — closes the feedback loop. Without it, lessons-learned is theater.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Capturing knowledge during and at the end of a project (milestone close, post-incident, full close-out).</item>
        <item>Building a searchable, structured organizational memory across many projects.</item>
        <item>Onboarding new PMs / engineers with curated patterns and anti-patterns.</item>
        <item>Feeding a continuous-improvement loop: lesson → updated checklist → applied next sprint / project.</item>
        <item>Post-incident reviews (PIR / blameless postmortems) when the incident touched scope / cost / schedule.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>One-person, one-week project — overhead exceeds value; a 5-line note in the README is enough.</item>
        <item>Already-mature org with strong RCA culture and a working knowledge base — just contribute, don't re-invent the methodology.</item>
        <item>Live incident — capture facts now, lessons later. Do not derail incident response with a retro.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="Mandatory Structured Fields">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Reject any lesson submission that is missing a field or contains "TBD". Required: title (action-oriented, under 80 chars), project, date, category, impact_level with quantified effect, situation (facts only), root_cause (5-whys), lesson (generalizable, under 2 sentences), recommendation (action verb + owner_role + where_applied), evidence (artifact links).</statement>
        <rationale>Free-text lessons degrade to noise within months; structured fields enforce the information quality required for retrieval and application.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Reject "communication was bad" and any entry where symptom equals cause. Push back with: "go one level deeper — what specifically broke, and why?"</statement>
        <rationale>Vague entries produce vague recommendations; "improve communication" cannot be actioned or measured. A specific mechanism and fix can.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Quantify impact in dollars, days, defects, or incidents. "Saved time" is not a lesson; "avoided 12 dev-days of rework" is.</statement>
        <rationale>Quantified impact enables prioritization: a lesson that saved 12 dev-days should be in the kickoff checklist; one that saved 30 minutes should not be.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Continuous Capture Triggers">
      <rule>
        <statement>Capture lessons at each of these triggers, not only at project close-out: after each milestone, when a problem occurs, after a significant success, during retrospectives, at vendor handoffs, and at project closure.</statement>
        <rationale>End-of-project capture misses 60-80% of lessons; details are forgotten and the team has moved on. Continuous capture is the only way to preserve context.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Technical lesson with 5-whys depth">
        <note>Technical lesson: chose a new framework without prior team experience. Impact: development took 40% longer (est. 12 dev-days lost). Root cause: excitement about technology + underestimated training time (5-why: why did scope of training not appear in estimates? — because new tech was not flagged as a risk during kickoff). Lesson: new technology adoption requires explicit training time in the WBS. Recommendation: when introducing unfamiliar tech, add 25% buffer to estimates + schedule dedicated training. Owner: PM. Where applied: planning checklist.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Session Ground Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run lessons-learned sessions blameless: focus on systems and processes, not individuals. Apply 5-whys and reject "human error" as a terminal cause.</statement>
        <rationale>Blame culture turns sessions into theater; people stop sharing real failures. Blameless sessions produce actionable root causes that can change the system rather than the person.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Session structure (75 min): opening + ground rules 5min, what worked 15min, what did not work 15min, root causes 15min, recommendations 15min, action items with owners 10min.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Storage Requirements">
      <rule>
        <statement>Store lessons in a versioned repository (git or equivalent) with a controlled tag taxonomy. Inconsistent tags make lessons unfindable at kickoff retrieval.</statement>
        <rationale>A searchable corpus requires consistent categorization; without it, semantic search retrieves shallow matches and the repository becomes a graveyard.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Add a last_validated_on field to every lesson. Review tooling-specific lessons annually; expire at 24 months. Process and team lessons expire at 5 years. Mark expired lessons as archived, not deleted.</statement>
        <rationale>Tooling lessons go stale quickly as stacks change; recommending a deprecated approach is worse than no recommendation.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Application SLO">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>At every project kickoff, retrieve relevant lessons by tag and similarity and insert them into the planning checklist. Track application rate: of last quarter's lessons, what percent triggered a documented process change? Target: above 50%.</statement>
        <rationale>Lessons that are captured but not applied provide zero value; the application rate is the only metric that distinguishes a knowledge system from a documentation exercise.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>If application rate falls below 30% for two consecutive quarters, declare the storage or retrieval system broken and redesign the workflow before adding more lessons.</statement>
        <rationale>Adding more lessons to an unused system increases storage cost without benefit; the constraint is retrieval and application, not volume.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Anti-Patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Lessons held only at project close-out.</description>
        <reason>Small, frequent lessons are forgotten over a multi-month project; by close-out only major events are recalled, and even those lose context details.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Lessons stored in a wiki without a tag taxonomy or search capability.</description>
        <reason>An unsearchable repository means lessons cannot be retrieved at kickoff; they effectively do not exist for the next project team.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Recommendations written as "consider Y" or "be more careful".</description>
        <reason>Vague recommendations cannot be actioned, measured, or assigned. Every recommendation requires an action verb, an owner role, and a point of application.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Workflow Patterns">
      <p>The agent's job is to enforce structure, surface relevance, and close the application loop. Three phases: (1) capture — agent prompts at milestones, after problems, after wins, with a structured form (Situation → Impact → Root Cause → Lesson → Recommendation); writes to a single canonical store. (2) curation — periodic dedup, categorization, severity tagging, expiration of stale lessons. (3) application — at project kickoff, agent retrieves relevant lessons by tag / similarity and inserts them into the planning checklist. Treat the lessons store like a code repo: versioned, reviewed, indexed.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents:</p>
      <list>
        <item>A lesson-capturer subagent (define inline) — interactive prompt, enforces structured fields, never accepts vague entries.</item>
        <item>A lesson-curator subagent — weekly cron: dedup, categorize, mark stale (&gt; 24 months for tooling, &gt; 5 years for process).</item>
        <item>A lesson-retriever subagent (RAG-style) — at project kickoff, pulls top-k relevant lessons via embedding search + tag filter.</item>
        <item>password-scrubber — sweep lessons before publication; people paste credentials into "what went wrong" boxes.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Prompt pattern:</p>
      <code lang="text"><![CDATA[You are capturing a lesson. Required fields:
- title (≤ 80 chars, action-oriented)
- project, date, category (planning|execution|technical|team|vendor|stakeholder|security)
- impact_level (high|medium|low) with quantified effect (days delayed, $ overrun, incidents)
- situation (what happened, ≤ 5 sentences, facts only)
- root_cause (5-whys output; reject "human error" without depth)
- lesson (≤ 2 sentences, generalizable)
- recommendation (specific, with owner_role and where_applied: planning|kickoff|review|standup)
- evidence (links to artifacts, metrics)
Reject submission if any field empty or "TBD".
Reject "communication was bad" — push for specific mechanism + fix.]]></code>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools and Services">
      <p>CLI tools for lessons management and retrieval:</p>
      <list>
        <item>git — Lessons-as-code: Markdown files, PR review per lesson; https://git-scm.com/</item>
        <item>jq — Query lessons store JSON; https://stedolan.github.io/jq/</item>
        <item>ripgrep (rg) — Full-text search across lesson corpus; https://github.com/BurntSushi/ripgrep</item>
        <item>chromadb / qdrant / weaviate CLIs — Embedding-based retrieval for relevance search; https://www.trychroma.com/</item>
        <item>notion-cli / confluence-cli — Programmatic write to existing wiki; https://developers.notion.com/</item>
        <item>dataview (Obsidian) — Local PKM-style lesson queries; https://blacksmithgu.github.io/obsidian-dataview/</item>
        <item>pandoc — Export lesson summaries to PDF / DOCX for execs; https://pandoc.org/</item>
      </list>
      <p>Services and platforms for lessons storage and retrieval:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Notion (SaaS) — Lessons DB with rich tags; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Confluence (SaaS / on-prem) — Enterprise standard; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Obsidian + sync (OSS / SaaS) — Local-first; agent via filesystem; partial agent support</item>
        <item>GitHub / GitLab repo (SaaS / on-prem) — Lessons-as-code; PR review enforces quality; REST + git; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Glean / Mem (SaaS) — Cross-tool retrieval; auto-relevance; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Coda (SaaS) — Structured + tabular; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Linear Insights (SaaS) — Project-level retrospectives + linkback; partial agent support</item>
        <item>Parabol / EasyRetro (SaaS) — Retro tools that export to lessons store; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Backstage TechDocs (OSS) — Internal-developer-portal lessons section; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Atlassian Compass (SaaS) — Component-level lessons + scorecards; REST API; agent-friendly</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Capture continuously, not just at close-out. Trigger after milestones, incidents, retros, vendor handoffs.</item>
        <item>Enforce a structured schema (Situation, Impact, Root Cause, Lesson, Recommendation). Free-text degrades to noise.</item>
        <item>Quantify impact ($, days, defects, incidents). "Saved time" is not a lesson; "saved 12 dev-days" is.</item>
        <item>Tie every lesson to an applied outcome: updated checklist, new test, PR template, training module. Untouched lessons are theater.</item>
        <item>Track lesson-application rate as an SLO: of last quarter's lessons, what % triggered a process change?</item>
        <item>Make the store findable: tag taxonomy + embedding search + project-kickoff retrieval ritual.</item>
        <item>Run blameless: focus on systems, not people. Use 5-whys; reject "human error" as terminal cause.</item>
        <item>Expire stale lessons; tooling-specific lessons go stale fast. A last_validated_on field with annual review keeps the corpus alive.</item>
        <item>Distribute by audience: PMO gets executive summary, engineering gets technical lessons, sponsors get one-pager.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>LLMs generate plausible but vague lessons ("improve communication", "be more proactive"). Force structured fields with rejection on vague input.</item>
        <item>5-whys done by an LLM tends to be a one-pass narrative, not real root-cause depth. Force iteration: "go one level deeper, what caused that?"</item>
        <item>Agents conflate symptom and cause. Add explicit fields: symptom, cause, lesson. Reject if symptom == cause.</item>
        <item>Retrieval is only as good as the tags. Without a controlled tag taxonomy, agent search returns shallow matches. Curate the taxonomy.</item>
        <item>LLM hallucinates "we did X" details when summarizing — always require evidence links; reject lessons with no artifacts.</item>
        <item>"Recommendation" output drifts to the bland — "consider doing Y". Force: action verb + owner_role + where_applied.</item>
        <item>PII / secrets in lesson text: postmortems often paste log lines with tokens. Run a scrubber pass before commit.</item>
        <item>Cross-team transfer: a lesson from team A applied blindly to team B can be wrong (different stack, different constraints). Tag with applicability scope.</item>
        <item>Lesson corpus drift over years: agents trained on old lessons recommend deprecated tools. Add last_validated_on; filter retrieval by recency for tooling category.</item>
        <item>Privacy: blameless culture is policy + tooling. Anonymize names by default; allow opt-in attribution for credit on positive lessons.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/lesson-record.md" purpose="Single lesson document with all five required fields" />
      <template path="templates/session-agenda.md" purpose="Facilitated lessons-learned session agenda (75 min)" />
    </templates>
